Intro to R: Analyzing the GWAS Catalog

Peter Carbonetto

February 7, 2017

1 About this document

This is an R Markdown Notebook. R Markdown combines Markdown, a popular, easy-to-read plain text formatting syntax, with chunks of R code. R Markdown notebooks can be easily rendered into various formats (PDF, HTML, etc.) for sharing your code and results with collaborators.

This notebook contains code to reproduce some of my analyses of data from the NHGRI-EBI GWAS Catalog. The GWAS Catalog provides results from thousands of genome-wide association studies of inherited diseases and completx traits. My aim in using the GWAS Catalog is to illustrate using R to process and analyze large-scale, complex tabular data.

For background on the GWAS Catalog, see the GWAS Catalog paper. See also the GWAS Diagram for an evocative visual summary of the data.

2 How to use this document

There are several ways to view this document:

  1. The simplest option is to open it up in a text editor. I recommend choosing a text editor that has syntax highlighting for Markdown, such as emacs or Atom.

  2. Open this file in RStudio (see below for details).

  3. Render, or knit, this notebook into a format that is pleasant to read on the screen, such as PDF or HTML. In the same folder as this file, I have provided an example of an HTML file rendered from this document, which can be viewed in your favourite Web browser.

2.1 This notebook is an interactive document

Although you caneasily generate all the output and figures with a single command from thermarkdown package (see below), my recommendation is to step through the code and explanations, and run the code on your own by copying and pasting the code into the R console, or by using the Run menu in RStudio.

4 Setting up your R programming environment

There are several options for setting up your R programming environment. In this section, we will explore some of the R environment options that are available on the midway compute cluster and on your laptop. No single option is best for everyone.

4.1 R on your laptop

I recommend installing both R and RStudio.

  1. Install the latest precompiled binary distribution of R by following the instructions on the CRAN website. This provides a text-based R programming environment.

  2. Next, install the free version of RStudio Desktop from here. RStudio provides a complete IDE (integrated development environment) for R programming.

  3. Try running R and RStudio on your computer. You can also try running R from a command-line shell (e.g., iTerm2 on Mac, Cygwin on Windows). To do so, simply type R, and hit the enter key.

  4. Test your R graphics setup; e.g., try copying and pasting the code chunk below into R or RStudio. in RStudio, this will (by default) draw the plot in the Plots tab. In R, this will render a plot on your screen, but only if you have X Windows software installed on your computer already. For example, for Mac OS X you need to have XQuartz.

library(lattice)
print(xyplot(dist ~ speed,cars,pch = 20,
             cex = 1.5,col = "dodgerblue"))

4.2 R on midway without graphics

Next, we explore how to run R in the command-line shell on the midway computer cluster. This approach is particularly useful for executing non-interactive computations in R; e.g., computations that may take several hours to run. I usually accompany the text-based R environment with a text editor (ideally one that has syntax highlighting) so that I can record my data analysis steps into an R script that can be run later.

I recommend using midway2 instead of midway1 because it has the most up-to-date version of R installed.

4.2.1 Getting a midway user account

If you do not already have a user account on midway, the instructor or helpers can provide you with a YubiKey. This will allow you to access midway for the duration of the workshop. (After the workshop, you can request a proper user account here provided you are associated with a Principal Investigator who already has an RCC account.)

To access midway using the YubiKey, when prompted for your username, enter rccguestXXXX, where XXXX is the last 4 digits shown on the Yubikey:

Whenever a password is requested for this guest account, the (very long) password will be automatically generated by lightly touching the metal contact:

4.2.2 Connecting to midway

Log on to midway2 using ssh:

ssh -X username@midway2.rcc.uchicago.edu

If you do not have an ssh program, or you are not sure how to access it, move to the next section, R on midway with graphics.

To illustrate best practice, we will request an interactive session to allocate computational resources for our computations in R:

sinteractive --time=02:00:00 --mem=2G --reservation=r_workshop

Outside the workshop, you will have to remove the --reservation=r_workshop portion of this command.

See here for more details on connecting to the midway compute cluster.

(To safeguard against losing your Internet connection, I recommend using the screen command before running sinteractive. Explaining this command is outside the scope of this workshop, but you can read a tutorial on the screen command here.)

4.2.3 Loading and running R

Load the R 3.3 module, and start R:

module load R/3.3
R --no-save

I include the --no-save flag because I dont like being asked whether I want to save the results of my R session, but this is optional.

Once you are in R, lets print the first 5 rows of the Iris data table:

print(head(iris,n = 5))
  Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2  setosa
2          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2  setosa
3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2  setosa
4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2  setosa
5          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2  setosa

Once you have completed this step, quit R, and return to the shell environment:

quit()

Note: In later episodes, we will omit the part about quitting R, so please remember how to do this.

4.2.4 Running R code without entering the R environment

Although R is mainly used interactively, it is also possible to execute R code like other non-interactive programming languages (e.g., Java). To do this, we use the Rscript command:

Rscript -e "print(head(iris,n = 5))"

More commonly, Rscript is used to execute R code stored in a file; e.g., Rscript my_analysis.R.

4.3 R on midway with graphics

We have already explored R with graphics on your computer. How can we visualize data in R on the midway compute cluster? There are several ways to do this. The recommended approach is to run R or RStudio in ThinLinc. Although the ThinLinc graphics are not always crisp, it is the most reliable solution on our cluster.

  1. Log in to ThinLinc. The simplest option is to use the Web interface. However, one drawback is that it doesnt support copying and pasting very well. See here for more information on connecting to midway using ThinLinc.

  2. Open up a ROXTerm window by clicking the icon at the bottom that looks like a computer monitor.

  3. Connect to midway2 with X forwarding:

ssh -Y midway2-login1.rcc.uchicago.edu
  1. Load and run either RStudio or R (or both!):
module load R/3.3
module load rstudio
rstudio
R --no-save
  1. Test R graphics by copying and pasting the code chunk below into R and/or RStudio.
library(lattice)
print(xyplot(dist ~ speed,cars,pch = 20,
             cex = 1.5,col = "dodgerblue"))

5 Downloading the code

Now that we have explored several different R environment options, please choose one of them for the remainder of the workshop. You will need an environment that can generate graphics. The recommended option is to run R or RStudio on midway because we have already installed the packages that are necessary to complete this workshop.

In this section, we will download, or clone, all the files from the Github repository. There are several ways this can be done:

  1. Go to the Github webpage and click the green clone or download button.

  2. Download and unzip a ZIP file containing the entire repository (this may only work on the compute cluster):

wget https://github.com/rcc-uchicago/R-intro/archive/master.zip
unzip master.zip
mv R-intro-master R-intro
  1. Clone the repository using git (requires the git command):
git clone https://github.com/rcc-uchicago/R-intro.git R-intro

Whatever approach you use, in the end, you should have a folder on your computer, or in your midway home directory, called R-intro.

Think of the R-intro folder as the main project folder; all files relevant to our data analysis project (code, data, etc.) should be saved within this folder. This will allow us to more easily keep track of our work.

Next, we will retrieve the data for our data analysis project.

6 Downloading the data

  1. Download the file that contains all associations with added ontology either by clicking this link, or with the wget command:
wget http://www.ebi.ac.uk/gwas/api/search/downloads/alternative
mv alternative gwas_catalog.tsv
  1. Copy this file to the data folder in git repository, and rename this file as gwas_catalog.tsv. See here for details on what is contained in this file.

Once you have completed these steps, the R-intro folder should have the following file structure:

R-intro/
 LICENSE
 README.md
 conduct.md
 assets
 data
    README.md
    gwas_catalog.tsv
    gwas_catalog_small.xlsx
 docs
     README.md
     demo_gwas_catalog.Rmd
     demo_gwas_catalog.html

7 Setting the working directory in your R programming environment

Now return to your preferred R environment, either on your computer, or on the compute cluster. If you have exited, please repeat the steps above to start a new environment.

To perform the data analysis, we need to make sure that our R environment points to the analysis folder of our project directory. One way to do this is using the setwd function in R. For example, if the R-intro files are in the projects folder in my home directory, do the following in R or RStudio:

setwd("~/projects/R-intro")

Alternatively, RStudio has a Set Working Directory option in the Session menu.

You can find out what your working by typing getwd().
